  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 12, content: "What is \"Those people\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "あの人達 (あのひとたち)", a: "あれら人達 (あれらひとたち)", b: "あの人達 (あのひとたち)", c: "あれ人達 (あれひとたち)", explanation: "あの人達 (あのひとたち) means Those people in Japanese. It's grammatically not wrong to say あれらのひとたち. But, it's more common to say あのひとたち as just adding たち in the end is enough to indicate it's plural.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 13, content: "What is \"These people\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "この人達 (ひとたち)", a: "この人達 (ひとたち)", b: "これら人達 (これらひとたち)", c: "これ人達 (これひとたち)", explanation: "この人達 (このひとたち) means These people in Japanese. It's grammatically not wrong to say これらのひとたち. But, it's more common to say このひとたち as just adding たち in the end is enough to indicate it's plural.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 14, content: "What is \"Their people\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "その人達 (そのひとたち)", a: "それら人達 (それらひとたち)", b: "それ人達 (それひとたち)", c: "その人達 (そのひとたち)", explanation: "その人達 (そのひとたち) means Their people in Japanese. It's grammatically not wrong to say それらのひとたち. But, it's more common to say そのひとたち as just adding たち in the end is enough to indicate it's plural.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 15, content: "What is \"Those people\" in casual way?", correct_answer: "あいつら", a: "あいつり", b: "あえつら", c: "あいつら", explanation: "あいつら is the casual way of saying Those people. You can use it among friends, but, never use it in business setting. You could also say あいつたち. But, it's more common to say あいつら in casual form.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 16, content: "What is \"These people\" in casual way?", correct_answer: "こいつら", a: "こいつら", b: "こいつる", c: "こいたら", explanation: "こいつら is the casual way of saying These people. You can use it among friends, but, never use it in business setting. You could also say こいつたち. But, it's more common to say こいつら in casual form.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 3, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 1, road: 17, content: "What is \"Their people\" in casual way?", correct_answer: "そいつら", a: "さいつら", b: "そいつら", c: "しいつら", explanation: "そいつら is the casual way of saying Their people. You can use it among friends, but, never use it in business setting. You could also say そいつたち. But, it's more common to say そいつら in casual form.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 1, content: "What is \"Cute\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "かわいい", a: "こわい", b: "かわいい", c: "かわい", explanation: "かわいい means cute or pretty. All the adjective ends with the letter 「い」So, if you see the word which ends with い, you could assume the word is adjective.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 2, content: "How do you say \"She is cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょ________。", correct_answer: "はかわいいです", a: "もかわいいです", b: "はかわいいです", c: "ひかわいいです", explanation: "When we say \" ~is (am, are) ~ \", we say 「〜は〜です」. は is pronounced as わ when it's used after subject. です is a particle that makes the whole sentence polite.\nかのじょ + は + かわいい + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "genre_id", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 0, theme: 0, road: 0, content: "content", correct_answer: "correct_answer", a: "a", b: "b", c: "c", explanation: "explanation", image_name: "image_name", audio: "audio"},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 4, content: "How do you say \"Is she cute?\" in polite way?\nかのじょ___?", correct_answer: "はかわいいですか？", a: "はかわいいですよ？", b: "はかわいいですけ？", c: "はかわいいですか？", explanation: "When we ask question, we add か in the end of the sentence\nかのじょ + は + かわいい + です + か？", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 5, content: "How do you say \"Is she cute?\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___?", correct_answer: "かわいい", a: "かわいいな", b: "かわいいね", c: "かわいい", explanation: "In casual way, you only need to omit は and ですか. You can add の in the end of the sentence as option. But, whether adding の ot not is up to you. There is not much of difference.\nかのじょ + かわいい？\nかのじょ + かわいい + の？", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 6, content: "How do you say \"She isn't cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___です", correct_answer: "かわいくない", a: "かわいいない", b: "かわわくない", c: "かわいくない", explanation: "When we make adjective negative meaning, we change the last letter い to く, and then add ない after that.\nかのじょ + は + かわい + く + ない + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 7, content: "What is another way of saying \"She isn't cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくありません", a: "かわいくありんす", b: "かわいくありません", c: "かわいくないにゃー", explanation: "When we make adjective negative meaning, we change the last letter い to く, and then add ありません after that. It's exactly the same meaning as かわいくないです.\nかのじょ + は + かわい + く + ありません", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 8, content: "How do you say \"She isn't cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいくないね", a: "かわいくなる", b: "かわいくないね", c: "かわいいじゃない", explanation: "Again, you can omit は and です and add ね in the end of the sentence.\nかのじょ + かわい + く + ない + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 9, content: "What is another way of saying \"She isn't cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいくはないね", a: "かわいくはないね", b: "かわいくふないね", c: "かわいくさないね", explanation: "You can add は between かわいく and ないね, and it still means She is not cute. The difference between かわいくない and かわいくはない is that かわいくない is simply denying that the she is cute. So, she could be ugly. But, かわいくはない is saying She is not categorized as かわいい group. So, it implies that she is not ugly.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 10, content: "How do you say \"Isn't she cute?\" in polite way?\nかのじょ___?", correct_answer: "かわいくないですか", a: "かわいくないですか", b: "かわいくないです", c: "かわいくなかったですか", explanation: "Again, when you make the sentence question, you need to add か in the end of the senten. Also, although grammatically it's not correct, it sounds weird to add は or any particle after subject in the question form. When this negative question is said, the person is usually trying to get agreement.\nかのじょ + かわいくない + です + か？", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 11, content: "How do you say \"Isn't she cute?\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___?", correct_answer: "かわいくない", a: "かわいくない", b: "かわいい", c: "かわいじゃない", explanation: "In casual way, you only need to omit ですか? from the sentence. And, you can add の in the end of the sentence as option. But, unlike positive form, adding の makes a subtle difference. If you simply say かのじょ + かわいくない？, you are trying to get the agreement. But, if you say かのじょ + かわいくない + の？, it sounds like you were thinking that she was cute, but to confirm, you are asking or you are simply asking.\nかのじょ + かわいくない？ (Trying to get agreement)\nかのじょ + かわいくない + の？ (Asking or confirming)", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 12, content: "How do you say \"She is not ugly\" using the word かわいい in polite way?\nかのじょは___です", correct_answer: "かわいくなくはない", a: "かわいくないなくない", b: "かわいくなくはない", c: "かわいくないない", explanation: "When we say \"~is not not (adjective)\", we change the last letter of the adjective い to く and add ~なくはない after adjective, and add です after that.\nかのじょは + かわい + く + なくはない + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 13, content: "How do you say \"She is not ugly\" using the word かわいい in casual way?\nかのじょ___", correct_answer: "かわいくなくはないね", a: "かわいくないなくないに", b: "かわいくなくはないね", c: "かわいくなくはないぬ", explanation: "In casual form, you can add ね instead of です.\nかのじょ + かわい + く + なくはない + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 14, content: "How do you say \"She is too cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___", correct_answer: "かわいすぎるね", a: "かわいさぎるね", b: "かわいすぎるね", c: "かわいいすぎるね", explanation: "When we say \"~is too (adjective)\", we omit the last letter い of the adjective and add すぎる. And in casual way, you can add ね in the end.\nかのじょ + かわい + すぎる + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 15, content: "How do you say \"She is too cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___", correct_answer: "かわいすぎです", a: "かわいさぎです", b: "かわいすぎるです", c: "かわいいすぎです", explanation: "In polite way, you need to omit る and add です.\nかのじょは + かわい + すぎ + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 16, content: "How do you say \"She was cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいかったです", a: "かわいかたです", b: "かわいかつたです", c: "かわいかったです", explanation: "When we say \"~was (adjective)\", we omit the last letter い of the adjective and add かった, and add です\nかのじょは + かわい + かった + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 17, content: "How do you say \"She was cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいかった", a: "かわいかた", b: "かわいかつた", c: "かわいかった", explanation: "In casual form, you need to omit は and です and add ね in the end\nかのじょ + かわい + かった + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 18, content: "How do you say \"She wasn't cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなかったです", a: "かわいくないです", b: "かわいくなかったです", c: "かわいくなかたです", explanation: "Isn't cute is かわいくない. When we make it past tense, We omit the last letter of かわいくない and add かった, and add です\nかのじょは + かわいくな + かった + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 2, road: 19, content: "How do you say \"She wasn't cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなかったね", a: "かわいくなかたね", b: "かわいくなかったね", c: "かわいくなけたね", explanation: "In casual form, you need to omit は and です and add ね in the end\nかのじょ + かわい + かった + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 1, content: "How do you say \"If I was cute, it'd be the best thing\" in Japanese?\nもしわたしが____、さいこうだ (です)\nさいこう - Best", correct_answer: "かわいかったら", a: "かわいいなら", b: "かわいかったら", c: "かわいいから", explanation: "Whey we say \"If (subject) was (adjective)\", we first say もし which means If. After that we say the subject わたし and add が. There is no much difference between が and は. But, when the subject is in this type of sentence (If & When), it's more natural to add が instead of は. After that, you add the past form of adjective + ら. So, it,s かわいかった + ら.\nもし + わたし + が + かわいかった + ら + さいこう + だ (です)", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 2, content: "What is another way of saying \"If I was cute, it'd be the best thing\" in Japanese?\nもしわたしが____、さいこうだ (です)\nさいこう - Best", correct_answer: "かわいければ", a: "かわいかれば", b: "かわいくれば", c: "かわいければ", explanation: "Instead of かわいかったら, you can also say かわいければ. They are absolutely the same meaning. But, かったら is a bit more conversational. So, we change the last letter of the adjective い to け and add れば.\nもし + わたし + が + かわい + け + れば + さいこう + だ (です)", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 3, content: "How do you say \"If I wasn't cute, it'd be the worst thing\" in Japanese?\nもしわたしが____、さいていだ (です)\nさいてい - Worst", correct_answer: "かわいくなかったら", a: "かわいくなかったら", b: "かわいくなかたら", c: "かわいくなかったり", explanation: "The negative form of Was cute is かわいくなかった. So, you only need to add ら in the end.\nもし + わたし + が + かわいくなかった + ら + さいてい + だ (です)", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 4, content: "What is another way of saying \"If I wasn't cute, it'd be the worst thing\" in Japanese?\nもしわたしが____、さいこうだ (です)\nさいてい - Worst", correct_answer: "かわいくなければ", a: "かわいくなきれば", b: "かわいくなかれば", c: "かわいくなければ", explanation: "Instead of かわいくなかったら, you can also say かわいくなければ. They are absolutely the same meaning. But, かったら is a bit more conversational. We change the last letter of the adjective い to け and add れば.\nもし + わたし + が + かわいくな + け + れば + さいこう + だ (です)", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 5, content: "How do you say \"Because I'm cute, I'm popular\" in Japanese?\nわたしは____、もてます\nもてる - Popular\nもてます - Popular (polite)", correct_answer: "かわいいから", a: "かわいいのに", b: "かわいいけど", c: "かわいいから", explanation: "When we say \"Because (subjet) (adjective)\", we add から after the adjective.\nわたしは + かわいい + から + もてます", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 6, content: "How do you say \"Because I'm not cute, I'm not popular\" in Japanese?\nわたしは____、もてません\nもてない - Not popular\nもてません - Not popular (polite)", correct_answer: "かわいくないから", a: "かわいいじゃないから", b: "かわいくないから", c: "かわいくなから", explanation: "Not cute is かわいくない. So, you only need to add から after that.\nわたしは + かわいくない + から + もてません", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 7, content: "How do you say \"Although I'm cute, I'm not popular\" in Japanese?\nわたしは____、もてません\nもてない - Not popular\nもてません - Not popular (polite)", correct_answer: "かわいいのに", a: "かわいいなのに", b: "かわいいだけど", c: "かわいいのに", explanation: "When we say \"Although (subjet) (adjective)\", we add のに after the adjective.\nわたしは + かわいい + のに + もてません", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 8, content: "What is another way of saying \"Although I'm cute, I'm not popular\" in Japanese?\nわたしは____、もてません\nもてない - Not popular\nもてません - Not popular (polite)", correct_answer: "かわいいけど", a: "かわいいけだ", b: "かわいいだけど", c: "かわいいけど", explanation: "When we say \"Although (subjet) (adjective)\", we add けど after the adjective. It's absolutely the same meaning as のに.\nわたしは + かわいい + けど + もてません", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 9, content: "How do you say \"Even if I'm not cute, I will be popular\" in Japanese?\nわたしは____、もてます\nもてる - Popular\nもてます - Popular (polite)", correct_answer: "かわいくなくても", a: "かわいくなくても", b: "かわいくても", c: "かわいくなっても", explanation: "Not cute is かわいくない. When we say \"Even if I'm not cute\", we change the last letter of the adjective い to く, and add ても\nわたしは + かわいくな + く + ても + もてます", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 10, content: "What is \"Smart\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "賢い (かしこい)", a: "かしこお", b: "可視光 (かしこう)", c: "賢い (かしこい)", explanation: "賢い (かしこい) means smart.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 11, content: "How do you say \"She is cute and smart?\" in Japanese?\nかのじょは___です", correct_answer: "かわいくてかしこい", a: "かわいいくてかしこい", b: "かわいくてかしこくて", c: "かわいくてかしこい", explanation: "When we say \"~is (adjective) and (adjective)\", we change the last letter of the first adjective い to く and then add て, and then add the second adjective. You don't need to change the form of the second adjective.\nかわい + く + て + かしこい", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 12, content: "What is \"Strong\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "強い (つよい)", a: "儚い (はかない)", b: "尊い (とうとい)", c: "強い (つよい)", explanation: "強い (つよい) means strong.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 13, content: "How do you say \"She is cute, smart, and strong?\" in Japanese?\nかのじょは___です", correct_answer: "かわいくて、かしこくて、つよい", a: "かわいくて、かしこくて、つよくて", b: "かわいいくて、かしこいくて、つよい", c: "かわいくて、かしこくて、つよい", explanation: "Like the previous question, you change the last letter of the first and second adjective to く and add て after that. Only the last adjective won't change the form.\nかわい + く + て +　かしこ + く +て + つよい", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 5, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 14, content: "What is \"Noisy\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "うるさい", a: "うるさい", b: "うるしい", c: "うるせい", explanation: "うるさい means noisy.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 2, theme: 2, road: 15, content: "How do you say \"She is noisy but cute\" in Japanese?\nかのじょは___です", correct_answer: "うるさいけどかわいい", a: "うるさけどかわいい", b: "うるさいけどかわい", c: "うるさいけどかわいい", explanation: "When we say \"~is adjective but adjective\", we add けど after the first adjective and add second adjective.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 1, content: "How do you say \"She will become cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなるね", a: "かわいくなれね", b: "かわいくなるね", c: "かわいかなるね", explanation: "When we say \"~will become (adjective)\", we omit the last letter of the adjective い and add くなる, and add ね\nかわい + くなる + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 2, content: "How do you say \"She will become cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなります", a: "かわいくなるです", b: "かわいくなります", c: "かわいくなりです", explanation: "〜くなる is a subsidiary verb. When you make the verb polite, you add ます instead of です. In this case, you change the last letter of る to り and add ます.\nかわい + くなり + ます", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 3, content: "How do you say \"She can become cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなれるね", a: "かわくなるね", b: "かわいくなれるね", c: "かわいくなりね", explanation: "When we say \"~can become (adjective)\", we omit the last letter of the adjective い and add くなれる, and add ね\nかわい + くなる + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 4, content: "How do you say \"She can become cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなれます", a: "かわいくなれです", b: "かわいくなれます", c: "かわいくなります", explanation: "〜くなれる is a subsidiary verb. When you make the verb polite, you add ます instead of です. In this case, you omit the last letter of る and add ます.\nかわい + くなれ + ます", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 5, content: "How do you say \"She became cute\" in casual way?\nかのじょ___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなったね", a: "かわいくなったね", b: "かわいくなりたね", c: "かわいくなるたね", explanation: "When we say \"~became (adjective)\", we omit the last letter of the adjective い and add くなった, and add ね\nかわい + くなった + ね", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 6, content: "How do you say \"She became cute\" in polite way?\nかのじょは___。", correct_answer: "かわいくなりました", a: "かわいくなったです", b: "かわいくなりました", c: "かわいくなったました", explanation: "In polite form, you change the last letter of かわいくなる to り and add ました\nかわい + くなり + ました", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 7, content: "How do you say \"Let's become cute\" in casual way?\n_____。", correct_answer: "かわいくなろう", a: "かわいくなり", b: "かわいくなろ", c: "かわいくなろう", explanation: "When we say \"Let's become (adjective)\", we change the last letter of the adjective い to く and add なろう.\nかわい + く + なろう", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 8, content: "How do you say \"Let's become cute\" in polite way?\n_____。", correct_answer: "かわいくなりましょう", a: "かわいくなろうです", b: "かわいくなりまし", c: "かわいくなりましょう", explanation: "In polite form, you need to change the last letter of る to り and add ましょう\nかわい + くなり + ましょう", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 9, content: "How do you say \"I want to become cute\" in polite way?\nわたしは____。", correct_answer: "かわいくなりたいです", a: "かわいくなるたいです", b: "かわいくなるです", c: "かわいくなりたいです", explanation: "When we say \"Want to become (adjective)\", we change the last letter of the word かわいくなる (will become cute) to り and add たい, and you can add です to make it polite in the end.\nかわいくな + り + たい + です", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 3, theme: 2, road: 10, content: "How do you say \"I want to become cute\" in casual way?\n____。", correct_answer: "かわいくなりたい", a: "かわいくなりたい", b: "かわいくなるたい", c: "かわいくなろう", explanation: "In casual form, you can omit です. And, you don't have to add any particle in the end of the sentence for this type of self-desire. Furthermore, you don't have to say わたし as it's obvious that who wants to become cute.\nかわいくな + り + たい", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 8, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 1, content: "What is \"Run\"(verb) in Japanese?", correct_answer: "走(はし)る", a: "走(はし)る", b: "書(か)く", c: "騒(さわ)ぐ", explanation: "走(はし)る means Run in Japanese.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "a", subgenre_id: 6, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 2, content: "What is \"Every day\" in Japanese?", correct_answer: "毎日 (まいにち)", a: "参日 (さんにち)", b: "毎日 (まいにち)", c: "今日 (きょう)", explanation: "毎日 (まいにち) means Every day.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 3, content: "How do you say \"I run everyday\"?\nわたしは、まいにち___。", correct_answer: "はしります", a: "はしります", b: "はしるます", c: "はしらます", explanation: "When we say \"I run everyday\", we add は after subject and change the last letter of verb る to り and add ます.\nわたし + は + はし + り + ます\nます is a suffix that makes the whole sentence polite.\nまいにち works as adverb and it has to be placed before verb. So, it can be placed before or after わたしは.\nわたしは + まいにち + はしります\nor\nまいにち + わたしは + はしります", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 4, content: "How do you say \"I run everyday\" in casual way?\nわたし、まいにち___。", correct_answer: "はしるよ", a: "はしれよ", b: "はしるよ", c: "はしりよ", explanation: "In casual way, は and ます can be omitted. And instead of ます, you can add よ in the end of the sentence. It makes the whole sentence sound like you are actually telling the sentence to that person. If there is no suffix, it sounds like you are robot.\nFYI, this suffix よ can be different depending on where he or she is from. For example, People from west (Kansai) may add ねん in the end instead of よ.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 5, content: "How do you say \"I will run everyday this week\"?\nわたしは、こんしゅう、まいにち___。", correct_answer: "はしります", a: "はしります", b: "はしれます", c: "はしろう", explanation: "We don't have \"Will\" in our grammar. So, when we talk about future, we use the same form as the present tense, which is はしります in this case. You can judge if it's about the present or future tense only by the context.\nIn addition, when we talk about date & time, we say the bigger scale first. So, it goes with こんしゅう、まいにち", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 6, content: "How do you say \"I will run everyday this week\" in casual way?\nわたし、こんしゅう、まいにち___。", correct_answer: "はしるよ", a: "はしるか", b: "はしるよ", c: "はしるし", explanation: "In casual form, we don't have \"Will\" as well. So, you can simply add よ after はしる. You can also omit は after subject.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 7, content: "How do you say \"Will you run every day this week\" ?\nあなたは、こんしゅう、まいにち、___？", correct_answer: "はしりますか", a: "はしりますか", b: "はしれますか", c: "はしるますか", explanation: "When we ask \"Will you (verb)?\", we change the last letter る to り, and add ます and か. So, it's\nはしり + ます + か", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 8, content: "How do you say \"Will you run every day this week\" in casual way?\nあなた、こんしゅう、まいにち、___？", correct_answer: "はしるの", a: "はしるよ", b: "はしるね", c: "はしるの", explanation: "In casual form, you can simply add の after はしる. You can also omit は after subject.", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 9, content: "How do you say \"I ran yesterday\" in Japanese?\nわたしは、きのう、___。", correct_answer: "はしりました", a: "はしるました", b: "はしりました", c: "はしたました", explanation: "When we talk about past, we change the last letter る to り and add まし and add た. So, it's\nはし + り + まし +た\n", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 10, content: "How do you say \"I ran yesterday\" in casual way?\nわたしは、きのう、___。", correct_answer: "はしったよ", a: "はしりたよ", b: "はしるたよ", c: "はしったよ", explanation: "When we talk about past in casual form, \nwe change る to 「っ」 and add た and add suffix よ. So, it's \nはし + っ + た + よ\nWhen the last letter of verb ends with る, and it changes the form like ら→り→る→れ→ろ, you change る to 「っ」 and add た in the past form. ", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 11, content: "How do you say \"Run!!\" in Japanese?\n_____!!", correct_answer: "はしれ", a: "はしる", b: "はしれ", c: "はしり", explanation: "When we order \"Run\" to others, we change the last letter る to れ. So, it's\nはし + れ", image_name: "", audio: ""},
  {genre_id: "b", subgenre_id: 0, thirdgenre_id: 0, level: 1, theme: 3, road: 12, content: "How do you say \"Let's run\" in Japanese?\n_____", correct_answer: "はしろう", a: "はしろう", b: "はしれよ", c: "はしるう", explanation: "When we say \"Let's run\", we change the last letter る to ろ and add う. So, it's\nはし + ろ + う", image_name: "", audio: ""}
])
